definition:
(V.) man-‘become ash’; mi–an ‘get ashes on self’;
-an [abwan] ‘scour (using ash)’.
(N.) ashes.

(N.) athletes’ foot.
(D.) maqalipungan ‘suffering from athletes’ foot’;
makayalipungaq ‘conducive to a.f.’.

(N.) blue.
(D.) ma-asul ‘dark blue’; ma-asulasul ‘light blue’;
maka-asul ‘wearing blue clothes’.

(N.) mangrove wood (used for firewood);
baka’wan mangroves ‘where wood is collected
for charcoal’.

(N.) fence.
(V.) mag-bakud, magpabakud ‘put up a fence’;
bakur-an ‘fence something in’.

(N.) news, clue.
(V.) magbalitaq ‘spread news’; mamalitaq;
ibalitaq ‘tell someone something’; makibalitaq
‘share news’; balita’nan ‘inform someone’;
mibali’taq, mipamali’taq ‘be informed’.

(D.) slow (speech) (speed, e.g. in driving).
(V.) banayaran, benayaran ‘reduce speech’;
magbanayad ‘decelerate’.

(N.) bank, where one stores money.
(V.) magpabangko ‘put money in a bank’;
makapagpabangko. (St.) makibangko.

(N.) garbage. basure’ru ‘garbageman’;
basuraqan ‘garbage dump’.
(D.) mabasura ‘full of garbage’.

(N.) smell.
(V.) babau ‘smell’; bauan ‘smell something’;
a:babau; pa:mau; pa:mauan; makibau;
pakibau; pa:bau.
(D.) mabau.

(St./D.) prohibited. makabawal ‘prohibited’;
kabawalbawalan ‘really verboten’.
(V.) bawalan, bewalan ‘prohibit something’;
pa:mawal, pa:bawal, mamawal, pakibawal.

(V.) mag-bayansel [Eng. buy-and-sell] ‘work as
a middleman, work on black-market’;
mipagbayansel, pakipayansel.

(Q.) suddenly, straightaway. bigla:bigla’q.
(V.) pa:biglaq; pa:miglaq ‘do something’;
pamiglan ‘abruptly’.

(N.) visitor; see da’lo. pa:magbisita ‘visitation’.
(V.) mamisita ‘visit’; magbisita ‘visit’;
makibisita, pa:bisita, a:bisita, pakibisita.

(D.) stupid.
bolangbolang; kabolangan ‘very, very stupid’;
a:bolang; mekabolang.

(V.) whisper.
bubulung, bulungan ‘whisper something’;
bilungan, bilung; ma:mulung, pa:bulung;
a:bulung; mibubulungan.

(N.) horn (for blowing, auto horn).
(V.) bubusina ‘blow horn’; mamusina;
makibusina; pamusinan; ibusina.

(N.) button(s).
(V.) butunisan ‘button something up’;
mamutunis ‘one who puts on button’;
makapamutunis ‘can sew on button’.

(N.) length.
(V.) kakabaq, kakaban ‘lengthen something’;
magpakabaq ‘stretch self’; pakikabaq;
ikabaq; a:kabaq; pakabaq; pakaban;
mipakabaq.
(D.) makabaq; makabakabaq.

(N.) cabaret, nightclub + dance hall.
(V.) mangabaret ‘go to a cabaret’;
makapangabaret.

(N.) marriage, wedding.
talakasal, kasal-wes ‘civil ceremony’.
(V.) kakasal, kinasal, ke:sal; ikasal;
magpakasal; pa:kasal; pa:ngasal; a:kasal;
mipakasal.
(D.) makasal, me:kasal.

(N.) goodness; see mayap, qapqap, kumayap.
(V.) kayap, kumayap ‘get well, recover’;
mangayap; makakayap; pa:kayap;
pa:kayapan; a:pakayap.
(D.) makayap, mikayap, makikayap.

(N.) kerosene.
saynu-gas ‘cyanide (?)–a poison used on fish’;
sulung-degas ‘kerosene lantern’;
pididinan-gas ‘fuel-pump, valve’.

(N.) history; story.
(V.) magqistorya ‘tell a story’; manqistorya;
qistoryan ‘tell about something’;
makiqistorya.
(D.) maqistorya ‘talkative’.

(St./D./N.) excess.
pangalalu ‘envy, jealousy’; mangalalu ‘be envious;
milalalu; mapangalalu; lalung marok ‘worse’;
lalung marayuq ‘farther’.

(N.) face.
kalupa ‘look like (one with same face as another)’;
milupa ‘similar, same’.

(Subs., interrog., location) ‘where’; see ante;
alternate form: nu:.
144

(Number affix, forms ordinals with completed
aspect) banwang sikadwaq ‘two years ago’;
banwang sikatluq ‘three years ago’.

(N.) an iron bar used for digging in very hard soil;
see sur-gamat.
(V./St.) pisudsudsudsud ‘be mocked’.

(D.) masyas ‘tough, hard, crisp’.
masyas a amanu ‘tough speech (tensed vowels;
crude words)’; masyas a pesus ‘crisp peso bill’;
masyas a dutung ‘strong, hard wood’.
(V.) pa:syas ‘make strong, hard’.
